  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The federal statutes governing money laundering are primarily found in **Title 18, U.S. Code, Sections 1956 and 1957**. The penalties depend on the specific offense, the amount of money involved, and other factors, but generally include the following:\n\n### 1. **Criminal Penalties (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956)**  \n   - **Maximum Prison Sentence:** Up to **20 years per count**.\n   - **Fines:** Up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater. For corporations and organizations, fines can be up to **$1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n   - **Asset Forfeiture:** Any property involved in or traceable to the money laundering offense may be subject to forfeiture.\n\n### 2. **Criminal Penalties (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957)**  \n   - This section applies to transactions involving criminally derived property exceeding **$10,000** in value.  \n   - **Maximum Prison Sentence:** Up to **10 years per count**.  \n   - **Fines:** Up to **$250,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater. For organizations, fines can be up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n\n### 3. **Aggravated Penalties**  \n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from certain serious crimes (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, or other specified unlawful activities), penalties may be enhanced.  \n   - In cases involving **terrorist financing**, penalties can include additional prison time and higher fines.\n\n### 4. **Civil Penalties**  \n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities may face civil penalties, including fines and asset forfeiture.  \n   - Civil fines can be substantial, often exceeding the value of the laundered funds.\n\n### 5. **Additional Consequences**  \n   - **Record of Conviction:** A money laundering conviction can result in a permanent criminal record, affecting employment, professional licenses, and immigration status.  \n   - **Restitution:** Courts may order the defendant to pay restitution to victims of the underlying criminal activity.  \n   - **Supervised Release:** After serving a prison sentence, individuals may be placed on supervised release for a period of up to **3 years**.\n\n### 6. **Enforcement Agencies**  \n   - Money laundering cases are prosecuted by the **U.S. Department of Justice (DOJ)** and investigated by agencies such as the **Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)**, the **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)**, and the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**.\n\n### Key Takeaway:  \nMoney laundering is a felony offense with harsh penalties, including lengthy prison sentences, substantial fines, and asset forfeiture. The exact penalties depend on the circumstances of the case, such as the amount of money involved and the nature of the underlying criminal activity. Legal representation is critical for anyone facing money laundering charges.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
